Crashes in production—especially **background crashes**—are where senior engineers differentiate themselves. Let’s break this down in a **real-world, production-debugging mindset**.

---

# 🔥 PART 1: Why Apps Crash in Production (General)

Production crashes usually don’t show up in dev because of:

* Different data
* Real user behavior
* Device constraints (low memory, poor network)

## 🚨 1. Force unwraps (`!`)

Still one of the top crash reasons.

```swift
let name = user.name! // 💥 crash if nil
```

### Fix:

```swift
guard let name = user.name else { return }
```

---

## 🚨 2. Array out of bounds

```swift
let item = items[index] // 💥 crash if index invalid
```

### Happens when:

* Async updates modify array
* UI reads stale index

---

## 🚨 3. Threading issues (Main vs Background)

Updating UI from background thread:

```swift
DispatchQueue.global().async {
    self.label.text = "Hello" // 💥
}
```

### Fix:

```swift
DispatchQueue.main.async {
    self.label.text = "Hello"
}
```

---

## 🚨 4. Memory pressure / OOM (Out of Memory)

Common in:

* Image-heavy apps
* Infinite scroll lists
* Poor caching

Symptoms:

* No crash logs sometimes
* App just terminates

---

## 🚨 5. Networking edge cases

* API returns unexpected JSON
* Missing fields
* Timeout / retry loops

```swift
try JSONDecoder().decode(Model.self, from: data) // 💥
```

---

## 🚨 6. Core Data / DB corruption

* Migration issues
* Concurrent writes

---

## 🚨 7. Third-party SDK crashes

Analytics, ads, payments can crash in production only.

---

## 🚨 8. SwiftUI state inconsistencies

* Multiple sources of truth
* Rapid updates → invalid UI state

